    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm just starting to learn music theory and i keep hearing about the \"circle of fifths.\" can u explain how it actually works and how i'm supposed to use it to figure out what key a song is in?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Circle of Fifths is a map of the musical world that shows how every key relates to every other key by moving up or down a perfect fifth. To find a key, you simply trace a line from the starting note to the key you want to find, counting up or down the circle until you land on the correct key.\n\nImagine the circle is a giant, spinning wheel of musical notes where each key is a different color. If you start at C, moving clockwise takes you to G, B, D, F, A, E, and back to C. If you start at C and move counter-clockwise, you hit G, E, D, B, A, F, and back to C. This movement is exactly how you determine the key of a song.\n\nFor example, if a song starts on C and moves up a fifth, it lands on G. If it moves down a fifth, it lands on E. This simple rule lets you instantly figure out the key without needing to memorize every note individually. It's like a shortcut through the musical universe!",
      "source": "target",
